[StudyName "Training Visual Memory"]
[ChapterName "Task"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5WxYAxtW/rOJUyN5R"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.30"]
[UTCTime "12:01:41"]

{ They call it the mind's eye, or the place where you store information you have seen. High level athletes use this skill often to complete tasks, like judging the trajectory of a ball from the foot in order to meet it in the correct place before it arrives. Want to see it on a high level athlete? }
1. h3 { Christiano Ronaldo scores goals in the dark using visual memory: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aoScYO2osb0 } 1... h6 { The visual memory skill in chess helps in calculation - being able to move the pieces and still see them without actually moving them. This makes it an essential skill in every part of the game after the initial memorization of the opening sequence. } 2. a3 { This study handles the training of this skill - especially in very young chess players. If you are a coach and you find that you have young students stuck in the beginner phases of learning, often training visual memory can give them the boost they need to move forward. If you are an expert - there is a good chance that you have a strong visual memory already. } *


