[UTCTime "12:20:57"]

{ If a coach happens to have a group of students in person, this drill can be adapted for a very large group. Have each side drop their own queen onto the board and then quickly fill in the common squares using pawns. The player with more of their own color pawns on the board *correctly* gets a point. } { [%csl Gf3,Rb6,Gb2,Gc3,Gf7,Re6] }
 *


[Event "Training Visual Memory: Drill 1 - Advanced"]
[Date "2019.03.30"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Training Visual Memory"]
[ChapterName "Drill 1 - Advanced"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5WxYAxtW/6xTWP0tC"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "8/8/5Q2/8/2Q5/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.30"]
[UTCTime "12:23:15"]

{ The queen drill falls short of training visual memory for every piece in chess. There are only two linear pieces aside from the queen - namely the bishop and the rook. To train the knights also, add an advanced rule to the drill: The queens may also move like knights. This addition trains knight movement, and also adds a bagillion more squares to the Competition version of Drill 1 - assuming the queen's are placed close enough together. } { [%csl Bd6,Bb6,Be5,Ye4,Yd5,Yg4,Gd4,Gf4,Gh4,Gf1,Gf7,Yg8,Ge6,Gc3,Bb2,Gc6,Ga6][%cal Yf6d5,Yf6e4,Bc4d6,Bc4b6,Bc4e5,Yf6g4,Yf6g8,Bc4b2] }
 *


