{ Unfortunately, this drill is unplayable online at this time. You'll need a board and a real set of pieces to try it. A willing opponent is also helpful. Clear the board down to no pieces. As soon as you move a piece - it becomes visible, but you still have to remember all of the other pieces in their starting positions. }
 *


[Event "Training Visual Memory: Drill 2 - Half Blind Opening"]
[Date "2019.03.30"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Training Visual Memory"]
[ChapterName "Drill 2 - Half Blind Opening"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5WxYAxtW/dwovKc1A"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/4P3/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.30"]
[UTCTime "12:30:36"]

{ White has played 1.e4 in a half blind opening. The remaining 15 white pieces still exist, but are invisible until they have moved. After each move - run through the pieces on the back row in your mind and remember what they are and where they are. It also helps to notice when pieces are free to move - like the bishop at f1 is now free to develop. Do not move pieces through invisible pawns! }
 *


