[UTCTime "12:48:47"]

{ When starting out with this drill - it can help to have a chess board turned upside down in front of you. Ask yourself the question: Where on the chess board is the square I am trying to name. Place a marker or pawn in the rough location where the square might be if you could see it. You could also do this on an empty table, visualizing the chess board - or on a blank notebook etc. }
 *


[Event "Training Visual Memory: Drill 3 - Knight Moves"]
[Date "2019.03.30"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Training Visual Memory"]
[ChapterName "Drill 3 - Knight Moves"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5WxYAxtW/NCAynEoP"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.30"]
[UTCTime "12:37:01"]

{ When you are proficient in naming square colors blind - Add a knight to your mental chess board. Do not look at a chess board for this drill! Place it on a random square in your mind - we will put ours on d4 in this example. Without looking at a chess board, name the squares to which a knight may move on this turn. It might help to write your squares down in order to check them after. } { [%csl Yd4][%cal Bd4c6,Bd4e6,Bd4f5,Bd4f3,Bd4e2,Bd4c2,Bd4b3,Bd4b5] }
 *


[Event "Training Visual Memory: Drill 3 - Diagonals"]
[Date "2019.03.30"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Training Visual Memory"]
[ChapterName "Drill 3 - Diagonals"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5WxYAxtW/JLLLRyZP"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.30"]
[UTCTime "12:39:33"]

{ Do not look at a chess board during this drill! Name or write down two squares on the chess board - Visualize if they appear on the same diagonal without looking at the chess board. For example: do c3 and g6 fall on the same diagonal? Without looking at a chess board this is tricky at first. } { [%csl Yc3,Yg6] }
 *


[Event "Training Visual Memory: Drill 3 - Advanced"]
[Date "2019.03.30"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Training Visual Memory"]
[ChapterName "Drill 3 - Advanced"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5WxYAxtW/emLIPX57"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.30"]
[UTCTime "12:41:11"]

{ Do not look at a chess board for this drill! Start a knight on a1 in your visual memory. Look away from the Board and ask yourself how many squares it takes the knight to reach a random square. For this example we will use e5. We find that it takes 4 moves on its shortest path. If you really want a workout - count how many different paths the knight might take to reach e4 in 4 moves. You will find several. :) } { [%csl Ga1,Ge5][%cal Ga1c2,Gc2e3,Ge3g4,Gg4e5,Gc2d4,Gd4f3,Gc2b4,Gb4c6,Gc6e5,Gb4d3,Gd3e5,Gc2e1,Ge1f3,Gf3e5,Ge1d3,Ya1b3,Yb3d4,Yd4c6,Yb3c5,Yc5d7,Yd7e5,Yb3a5,Ya5c6,Ya5c4,Yc4e5] }
 *


[Event "Training Visual Memory: Drill 4 - Full Blind Opening"]
[Date "2019.03.30"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Training Visual Memory"]
[ChapterName "Drill 4 - Full Blind Opening"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/5WxYAxtW/AB5fqtTr"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/DrHack"]
[FEN "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2019.03.30"]
[UTCTime "12:45:19"]

{ This drill is how it sounds. Play the opening blind by yourself or with an opponent. Do not look at a chess board for this drill! Write down your moves on a scoresheet so you can check your moves for quality and legality. Play to move 5 and then check to see if you made all legal moves. Rinse and repeat for different openings. Go to move 7 - to move 10 - and then as far as you can go blind. Whenever an illegal move is made, or when you can no longer remember everything - play the game back from memory with real pieces. }
 *


